Americas
---
[1] USA (New York) ex Israel
Date: Wed 17 Oct 2018
Source: The Yeshiva World [edited]
https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/general/1606636/measles-outbreak-at-least-7-cases-in-monsey-6-in-williamsburg-some-travelled-to-israel-and-were-unvaccinated.html


The NYC Health Department today [17 Oct 2018] is reporting 6 individuals with confirmed measles this month in the Orthodox Jewish community in Williamsburg, Brooklyn. The initial case of measles was acquired by a child on a visit to Israel, where a large outbreak of the disease is occurring. The individuals with measles ranged in age from 11 months to 4 years. Of these children, 5 were unvaccinated prior to exposure, including 4 because vaccination was delayed and one who was too young to have received the vaccine. The 6th child had received one dose of the vaccine prior to exposure but was not yet immune. Complications include one child who was hospitalized with pneumonia and another child with an ear infection.

Meanwhile, health officials in Rockland County on Wednesday [17 Oct 2018] said there were 7 confirmed cases, and an additional 8 suspected cases being investigated involving a mix of adults and children. Rockland officials say 5 of the sickened can be traced to recent travel to Israel. Also, 2 additional cases are from exposure that occurred in the county.

Health officials have said anyone at locations in Rockland, Westchester and Bergen counties may have been exposed to the measles (see URL above for list of locations). To increase awareness about measles, the NYC Health Department will hold a meeting in Williamsburg with rabbis and elected officials tomorrow [18 Oct 2018], place ads in local newspapers and distribute posters to health care providers.

The 1st case in Rockland County of international travel was in late September [2018], and 2 more cases due to separate international travelers in early October [2018] are leading to more potential cases of measles among non-immune residents. County health officials offered a free vaccine on 11 Oct [2018] to residents who had been exposed. Now they are offering 2 more chances for a free vaccine.

"As we see more cases there is the potential for further exposure," said Rockland County Commissioner of Health Dr. Patricia Schnabel Ruppert. "The Rockland County Department of Health continues to investigate these cases and will keep residents informed of any updates. I recommend that residents make sure they and their families are up-to-date on their measles vaccinations."

Measles is highly contagious, so anyone who is not protected against measles is at risk of getting the disease. Individuals are considered protected or immune to measles if they were born before 1957, have received 2 doses of measles, mumps, rubella (MMR) vaccine, have had measles confirmed by a health care provider, or have a lab test confirming immunity.

YWN [Yeshiva World News] reported 2 weeks ago about the Menahel of Breslov Mosdos in Tzefas having been infected with the measles. He was listed in critical condition at the time of the news story [See ProMED-mail Measles update (61): Middle East ex Ukraine, Europe, USA 20181015.6090960]. There have been dozens of stories published by YWN in the past few months of measles alerts issued by authorities involving Frum people who have not been vaccinated.

[Byline: Yossi Taub]

