[According to the NYC Health Department, if one person catches measles, 90% of that person's non-immunized close contacts will also become infected. Measles typically spreads through coughing and sneezing, and the virus can live for up to 2 hours in the air.

Although not as deadly as now-eradicated smallpox, which looks similar to measles in its early stage, many do not realize how serious measles can be. In the pre-vaccine era, roughly 6000 measles deaths were reported in the US each year, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).

The vaccine was introduced in 1963, and measles was declared eliminated from the US in 2000. But as vaccination rates have dropped, the disease has experienced a comeback, particularly in Orthodox and other ultra-religious communities, such as the Amish.

The number of parents against mandatory vaccines, known as anti-vaxxers, has also increased, especially in the western states. The LA Times estimates that 10% of children in private and religious schools in California go without protection from childhood diseases.

As of 8 Sep 2018, 137 cases of measles have been confirmed in 24 states and the District of Columbia, the CDC says.

A study by Dr. Jennifer B. Rosen published in the academic journal JAMA Pediatrics in August 2018 found that the 2013 New York measles outbreak, with 58 cases, also broke out among unvaccinated children within Orthodox Jewish communities in Williamsburg and Borough Park.

Of the 58 confirmed Brooklyn cases, 45 (78%) were unvaccinated because of parental refusal or intentional delay, and 12 (21%) were too young for routine measles vaccination. Excerpted from http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2018/10/18/nyc-measles-outbreak-orthodox-williamsburg-stems-unvaccinated-children. - Mod.LK]

******
[2] Brazil
Date: Wed 17 Oct 2018
Source: Xinhua [edited]
http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-10/18/c_137541283.htm


Brazil's Health Ministry on Wed confirmed 2192 cases of measles, of which 12 have died. Most of the cases occurred in the northern region, in the states of Amazonas and Roraima, with 1776 and 330 cases, respectively. In addition to the confirmed cases, 7894 suspected cases are pending confirmation in these 2 states.

The health ministry highlighted that a large vaccination campaign is being carried out in the states where cases of measles were registered, with 13.2 million doses of vaccines shipped to those states since the beginning of the year [2018]. Brazil received a measles-free certification from the Pan-American Health Organization (PAHO) a few years ago. If the country does not manage to control the outbreak before February 2019, the certification may be rescinded.

